sec.p:
The world biodiversity of palpigrades remains largely unknown despite the enormous progress seen in the last 15–20 years. There are 114 species described to date (Bu et al. 2019; Souza & Ferreira 2020 ; Souza et al. 2020;
Bu et al. 2021
, in press), a number remarkably smaller as compared to other groups of arachnids; for example, there are about 2200 known species of scorpions ( Lourenço 2018 ), 220 of whip spiders (Amplypygi) (
Shakhatreh et al. 2020
), and 1200 of sun spiders (Solifugae) (
Botero-Trujillo et al . 2017
).

Palpigradi consists of two families: Eukoeneniidae Petrunkevitch, 1955 and
Prokoeneniidae Condé, 1996 . The Eukoenenian lineage includes the extant genera AllokoeneniaSilvestri, 1913 , Leptokoenenia Condé, 1965
, KoeneniodesSilvestri, 1913 and Eukoenenia Börner, 1901
. Allokoenenia is monotypic and it is represented only by the African species Allokoenenia afraSilvestri, 1913 . Leptokoenenia includes only five species: two found in ferruginous caves in Brazil , two inhabiting coastal ecosystems of Congo and Saudi Arabia and another found in the soil of a Quercus suber plantation in the coast of Italy . Koeneniodes contains eight species occurring in Asia and Africa ( Harvey 2003 ; Souza & Ferreira 2013 ;
Giribet et al. 2014
). Finally, Eukoenenia has 93 species distributed in all continents, except Antarctica ( Harvey 2003 ; Bu & Chen 2019 ; Souza & Ferreira 2020 ; Souza et al. 2020;
Bu et al. 2021
, in press). The family
Prokoeneniidae Condé, 1996 is composed of two genera, TriadokoeneniaCondé, 1991 with a single species from Madagascar and Prokoenenia Börner, 1901
with six species: three from Asia, two from North America and one from South America. In Asia, P. javanicaCondé, 1990 was described from Java, P. asiaticaCondé, 1994 from Thailand , and P. celebicaCondé, 1994 from Sulawesi ( Harvey 2003 ). These data reveal that about 80% of the species described belong to Eukoenenia , and that the other genera are represented by just a small number of species, most of them described in the 20th century.

